<section xml:id="sec-precalc-trig" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Trigonometry</title>

  <p>
    Trigonometric functions are fundamental tools in calculus.
    They arise in problems involving motion, waves, oscillations, and periodic behavior,
    and they play a key role in limits, derivatives, and integrals.
    In this section, we review the core definitions and properties of trigonometric functions
    that will be used throughout the course.
  </p>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-trig-triangle">
    <title>Right Triangle Definitions</title>

    <p>
      We begin by defining sine and cosine using right triangles.
      These definitions apply when the angle is acute.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-trig-triangle">
      <title>Sine and Cosine (Right Triangle)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given a right triangle and an acute angle <m>\theta</m>,
        </p>
        <me>
          \sin(\theta) = \dfrac{\text{opposite}}{\text{hypotenuse}},
          \qquad
          \cos(\theta) = \dfrac{\text{adjacent}}{\text{hypotenuse}}.
        </me>
      </statement>

      <figure xml:id="fig-trig-right-triangle">
        <caption>
          A right triangle illustrating the definitions of sine and cosine for an acute angle <m>\theta</m>.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/trigRightTriangle.PNG" width="60%"/>
      </figure>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In a right triangle, the side opposite <m>\theta</m> has length 3,
          the adjacent side has length 4, and the hypotenuse has length 5.
          Find <m>\sin(\theta)</m> and <m>\cos(\theta)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <me>
          \sin(\theta) = \dfrac{3}{5},
          \qquad
          \cos(\theta) = \dfrac{4}{5}.
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <remark>
      <p>
        While these definitions are intuitive, they apply only to acute angles.
        To extend trigonometric functions to all real numbers,
        we use the unit circle.
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-trig-unit-circle">
    <title>The Unit Circle Definition</title>

    <p>
      The unit circle allows us to define trigonometric functions
      for any real number and is the framework used in calculus.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-unit-circle">
      <title>Sine and Cosine (Unit Circle)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the unit circle centered at the origin.
          For a real number <m>\theta</m>, let the point on the unit circle
          corresponding to angle <m>\theta</m> (measured in radians)
          have coordinates <m>(x,y)</m>.
          Then
        </p>
        <me>
          \cos(\theta) = x,
          \qquad
          \sin(\theta) = y.
        </me>
      </statement>

      <figure xml:id="fig-unit-circle">
        <caption>
          The unit circle definition of sine and cosine.
          For an angle <m>\theta</m>, the point <m>(x,y)</m> on the unit circle satisfies
          <m>x = \cos(\theta)</m>, <m>y = \sin(\theta)</m>, and
          <m>\cos^2(\theta) + \sin^2(\theta) = 1</m>.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/trigUnitCircle.PNG" width="60%"/>
      </figure>
    </definition>

    <remark xml:id="rmk-radians-calculus">
      <p>
        In calculus, angles are always measured in radians.
        This choice ensures that derivatives and limits involving
        trigonometric functions behave correctly.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Evaluate <m>\sin(\pi/2)</m> and <m>\cos(\pi)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <me>
          \sin(\pi/2) = 1,
          \qquad
          \cos(\pi) = -1.
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <remark>
      <p>
        For acute angles, the unit circle and right triangle definitions of sine
        and cosine agree. The unit circle framework extends these ideas
        to all real angles.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <remark>
      <p>
        Because rotating by <m>2\pi</m> returns to the same point on the unit circle,
        sine and cosine are periodic with period <m>2\pi</m>.
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-trig-other-functions">
    <title>Other Trigonometric Functions</title>

    <p>
      In addition to sine and cosine, four other trigonometric functions
      are commonly used in calculus: tangent, secant, cosecant, and cotangent.
      These functions are defined in terms of sine and cosine.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-trig-ratios">
      <title>Definitions of Tangent, Secant, Cosecant, and Cotangent</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For an angle <m>\theta</m> such that the expressions are defined,
        </p>
        <me>
          \tan(\theta) = \dfrac{\sin(\theta)}{\cos(\theta)},
          \qquad
          \sec(\theta) = \dfrac{1}{\cos(\theta)},
        </me>
        <me>
          \csc(\theta) = \dfrac{1}{\sin(\theta)},
          \qquad
          \cot(\theta) = \dfrac{\cos(\theta)}{\sin(\theta)}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <remark>
      <p>
        Because these functions are defined as ratios,
        they are undefined whenever their denominators are zero.
        For example, since <m>\cos(\pi/2)=0</m>,
        both <m>\tan(\pi/2)</m> and <m>\sec(\pi/2)</m> are undefined.
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-trig-unit-circle-values">
    <title>Key Unit Circle Values</title>

    <p>
      Because calculus problems often require exact values rather than
      decimal approximations, it is important to know certain unit circle
      values without a calculator.
    </p>

    <p>
      The most important angles on the unit circle are
    </p>
    <me>
      0, \; \frac{\pi}{6}, \; \frac{\pi}{4}, \; \frac{\pi}{3}, \; \frac{\pi}{2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      The corresponding sine and cosine values are:
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{array}{c|cc}
        \theta &amp; \sin(\theta) &amp; \cos(\theta) \\ \hline
        0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 \\
        \dfrac{\pi}{6} &amp; \dfrac{1}{2} &amp; \dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\
        \dfrac{\pi}{4} &amp; \dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2} &amp; \dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \\
        \dfrac{\pi}{3} &amp; \dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} &amp; \dfrac{1}{2} \\
        \dfrac{\pi}{2} &amp; 1 &amp; 0
      \end{array}
    </me>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Evaluate <m>\sin(\pi/3)</m> and <m>\cos(\pi/4)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        These values can be read directly from the table:
      </p>
      <me>
        \sin(\pi/3) = \dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2},
        \qquad
        \cos(\pi/4) = \dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2}.
      </me>
    </solution>
  </example>

      <p>
        Values in other quadrants can be determined using symmetry
        and the signs of sine and cosine on the unit circle.
        On quizzes and exams, these values are expected to be known
        without a calculator.
      </p>
      

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Evaluate <m>\sin(5\pi/6)</m> and <m>\cos(5\pi/6)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The angle <m>5\pi/6</m> lies in Quadrant II and has reference angle
        <m>\pi/6</m>.
        In Quadrant II, sine is positive and cosine is negative.
      </p>
      <me>
        \sin(5\pi/6) = \sin(\pi/6) = \dfrac{1}{2},
        \qquad
        \cos(5\pi/6) = -\cos(\pi/6) = -\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}.
      </me>
    </solution>
  </example>


  </subsection>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-trig-range">
    <title>Range and Boundedness</title>

    <p>
      One of the most important properties of sine and cosine
      in calculus is that their values are bounded.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-sin-cos-range">
      <title>Range of Sine and Cosine</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For all real numbers <m>\theta</m>,
        </p>
        <me>
          -1 \le \sin(\theta) \le 1,
          \qquad
          -1 \le \cos(\theta) \le 1.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <remark>
      <p>
        This boundedness property is used frequently in calculus,
        especially when applying the Squeeze Theorem to evaluate limits.
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-trig-pythagorean-identities">
    <title>Pythagorean Identities</title>

    <p>
      One of the most important consequences of the unit circle definition
      of sine and cosine is a collection of identities that come directly
      from the Pythagorean Theorem.
    </p>

<theorem xml:id="thm-pythagorean-trig">
  <title>Pythagorean Identities</title>
  <statement>
    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
        \sin^2(\theta) + \cos^2(\theta) &amp; = &amp; 1 \\[4pt]
        1 + \tan^2(\theta) &amp; = &amp; \sec^2(\theta) \\[4pt]
        1 + \cot^2(\theta) &amp; = &amp; \csc^2(\theta)
      \end{array}
    </me>
  </statement>
</theorem>


  <p>
    Only the first identity,
    <m>\sin^2(\theta) + \cos^2(\theta) = 1</m>,
    needs to be memorized.
    The other two identities follow directly from it by dividing
    both sides by <m>\cos^2(\theta)</m> or <m>\sin^2(\theta)</m>,
    respectively.
  </p>



    <remark>
      <p>
        These identities provide different ways to express the same
        geometric relationship. In calculus, choosing the appropriate
        form often simplifies a computation.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Simplify the expression <m>1 + \tan^2(\theta)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <me>
          1 + \tan^2(\theta) = \sec^2(\theta).
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
<subsection xml:id="ssec-trig-identities-preview">
  <title>Angle Sum and Double Angle Formulas</title>

  <p>
    Trigonometric functions do not satisfy distributive or additive
    properties. Instead, they obey specific identities that describe
    how sine and cosine behave when angles are added or multiplied.
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-angle-sum">
    <title>Angle Sum Formulas</title>
    <statement>
      <me>
        \begin{array}{rcl}
          \sin(A+B) &amp; = &amp; \sin(A)\cos(B) + \cos(A)\sin(B) \\
          \cos(A+B) &amp; = &amp; \cos(A)\cos(B) - \sin(A)\sin(B)
        \end{array}
      </me>
    </statement>
  </theorem>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-double-angle">
    <title>Double Angle Formulas</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The double angle formulas are obtained by setting <m>B = A</m>
        in the angle sum formulas.
      </p>
      <me>
        \begin{array}{rcl}
          \sin(2A) &amp; = &amp; 2\sin(A)\cos(A) \\
          \cos(2A) &amp; = &amp; \cos^2(A) - \sin^2(A) \\
          &amp; = &amp; 2\cos^2(A) - 1 \\
          &amp; = &amp; 1 - 2\sin^2(A)
        \end{array}
      </me>
    </statement>
  </theorem>

</subsection>


